I know you&#39;ve accepted an answer but I just want to provide my own opinion. The first thing is that I don&#39;t think you want to use Abstract Factory pattern, it seems that you&#39;re not creating the objects but just want to locate client objects based on their name. That&#39;s the job for Locator, let&#39;s call it ClientLocator (for lack of better name). 

The idea is that you create a class called `ClientLocator` that implements `ApplicationContextAware`. By implementing this interface, Spring will inject an `ApplicationContext` object via a setter method. Using the `ApplicationContext` object, we can look for a bean by its name, afterwards we can check the type of the bean to make sure we get the correct one, and throw error when we don&#39;t.

Here&#39;s how the code looks.

**Clients**
```java
// SentimentClient.java
public interface SentimentClient {

    void call();

}


// FirstClient.java
@Service
public class FirstClient implements SentimentClient {


    @Override
    public void call() {
        System.out.println(&quot;Hello from the first client&quot;);
    }
}

// SecondClient.java
@Service
public class SecondClient implements SentimentClient {

    @Override
    public void call() {
        System.out.println(&quot;Hello from the second client&quot;);
    }
}


```

**ClientLocator.java**
```java

@Component
public class ClientLocator implements ApplicationContextAware {


    private ApplicationContext ctx;

    public SentimentClient get(String name) {
        return ctx.getBean(name + &quot;Client&quot;, SentimentClient.class);
    }

    @Override
    public void setApplicationContext(ApplicationContext ctx) throws BeansException {
        this.ctx = ctx;
    }
}

```

Here is how we can use the locator.

**ClientLocatorDemo.java**

```java
@Component
public class ClientLocatorDemo implements CommandLineRunner {

    @Autowired
    private ClientLocator clientLocator;

    @Override
    public void run(String... args) {
        SentimentClient firstClient = clientLocator.get(&quot;first&quot;);
        SentimentClient secondClient = clientLocator.get(&quot;second&quot;);

        firstClient.call();
        secondClient.call();

        // output:
        // Hello from the first client
        // Hello from the second client
    }
}


```

By doing this way, anytime a code wants to get a client by its name, just autowire the `ClientLocator` and call the `get(String name)` method. 

And the most important thing is that you can create client implementation as many as you like and get them by their name (assuming each has unique name and ends with &#39;Client&#39;) without having to autowire them one by one.

